The paper deals with theoretical computer science and specifically focuses on sparsification of graphs while preserving their properties. This falls under the category of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS) as well as computational geometry (cs.CG) since many of the sparsification problems involve geometric graphs. The paper also involves combinatorics (cs.DM) since it deals with counting and structural properties of graphs. Additionally, numerical analysis (cs.NA) may be relevant since some of the sparsification problems involve approximations. Finally, game theory (cs.GT) may also be relevant since some of the sparsification problems involve minimizing the cost of maintaining a network.
